<h1>@HI{{noni}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vplain{{}} @HI{{<strong>noni</strong>}}
<li> @Ai{{}} @HI{{<strong>noni</strong>}}
<li> @Ana{{}} @HI{{<strong>noni</strong>}}
<li> @N{{}} @HI{{na <strong>noni</strong>}}
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

Contrary to the expectations set by the clause preceding <strong>@HI{{noni}}</strong>, the clause following <strong>@HI{{noni}}</strong> is actually the case.
<p></p>

The speaker is in some way personally involved with the preceding clause.
<p></p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{@KJ{{every^day Sino^character}}wo @KJ{{exertion^study}}shite iru <strong>noni</strong> yoku @KJ{{memorize}}eraremasen.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Even though I study kanji every day I cannot memorise them well.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<strong>@HI{{noni}}</strong> carries some emotive overtones.
<p></p>

@HI{{ga}} can be used in place <strong>@HI{{noni}}</strong> although it is a weaker disjunctive. However, it is also free of the restrictions that apply to <strong>@HI{{noni}}</strong>. The clause
that precedes @HI{{ga}} may be in the polite style if the main clause is also in the polite style, whereas the clause preceding <strong>@HI{{noni}}</strong> is always in the plain style.
<p></p>

@HI{{keredo(mo)}}, and not <strong>@HI{{noni}}</strong>, must be used when:
<ul>
<li> the main clause involves a question, command, request or suggestion
<li> the main clause involves an expression of intention
</ul>
<p></p>

